Summarizing and exploring ontological results - generating benchmarks

Introduction

This document provides a repex for all figures in the publication Benchmarking Gene Ontology similarity methods and enabling their application.

Distance metrics

Anc2vec distances

activate the conda enviroment and create an var with GO term targets since the square matrix of all is too big.

library(reticulate)
## Warning: package 'reticulate' was built under R version 4.1.2
use_condaenv("anc2vec", required = T)
# reticulate::use_python("/Users/qwm753/opt/anaconda3/envs/anc2vec/bin/python")
import anc2vec
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.metrics.pairwise import cosine_similarity
import numpy as np

emb = anc2vec.get_embeddings()

df_emb = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(emb)
df_emb.shape
## (200, 44261)
df_emb = df_emb.transpose()

df_sim = cosine_similarity(df_emb)
df_sim = pd.DataFrame(df_sim, columns = df_emb.index.values)

exit
## Use exit() or Ctrl-D (i.e. EOF) to exit
anc2vec_dist <- py$df_sim
rownames(anc2vec_dist) <- colnames(anc2vec_dist)

Topology distance

Poor workaround, subsetting the available GO terms from anc2vec as its easier to do that rather than update anc2vec. If anc2vec has much higher performance i will revisit this.

mf_graph <- graph_from_go("MF", colnames(anc2vec_dist))
bp_graph <- graph_from_go("BP", colnames(anc2vec_dist))
cc_graph <- graph_from_go("CC", colnames(anc2vec_dist))
mf_neighbors <- lapply(
  V(mf_graph)$name, \(x){
    neighborhood(mf_graph,
                 order = 2,
                 x)[[1]] |> as_ids()
  }
)
sapply(mf_neighbors, length) |> hist(main = 'cluster size across all sample (without droping 50%)')

mf_neighbors <- mf_neighbors[sapply(mf_neighbors, length)<median(sapply(mf_neighbors, length))]
#retain only smaller than median for getting "realistic" cluster sizes
mf_neighbors <- mf_neighbors[sapply(mf_neighbors, length)>2]
# does 2 GO terms a cluster make?

mf_samples <- lapply(1:100, \(i){
  i <- sample(mf_neighbors, 10, replace = F)
  i <- sapply(i, \(ii){
    sample(ii, size = ceiling(length(ii) * .5))
  })
  i <- sapply(1:10, 
              \(ii) structure(rep(ii, length(i[[ii]])), names = i[[ii]])) |>
    unlist()
  i <- i[!names(i) %in% names(i)[duplicated(names(i))]]
})
bp_neighbors <- lapply(
  V(bp_graph)$name, \(x){
    neighborhood(bp_graph,
                 order = 2,
                 x)[[1]] |> as_ids()
  }
)
sapply(bp_neighbors, length) |> hist(main = 'cluster size across all sample (without droping 50%)')

median(sapply(bp_neighbors, length))
## [1] 26
bp_neighbors <- bp_neighbors[sapply(bp_neighbors, length)<median(sapply(bp_neighbors, length))]
bp_neighbors <- bp_neighbors[sapply(bp_neighbors, length)>2]

bp_samples <- lapply(1:100, \(i){
  i <- sample(bp_neighbors, 10, replace = F)
  i <- sapply(i, \(ii){
    sample(ii, size = ceiling(length(ii) * .5))
  })
  i <- sapply(1:10, 
              \(ii) structure(rep(ii, length(i[[ii]])), names = i[[ii]])) |>
    unlist()
  i <- i[!names(i) %in% names(i)[duplicated(names(i))]]
})
#save for amazon running
#save(list = c("bp_samples", "bp_graph"), file = "bp_sample.Rdata")

Reordering

truth <- lapply(c("mf_samples", "bp_samples"), function(x){
  x <- get(x)
  lapply(x, function(i){
    i <- as.factor(i)
    levels(i) <- 1:length(levels(i))
    structure(as.numeric(i), names = names(i))
  })
})

names(truth) <- c("Geodesic MF", "Geodesic BP")

Negative controls

lies <- lapply(truth, \(dist){
  lapply(dist, \(n){
    structure(sample(n, replace = F),
              names = names(n))
  })
})

Distance matrices

A small note on analysis not shown: tried to use the information borrowing effect of subsetting the graph in geodesic distance to the other clustering algorithms. Ie. in geodesic clustering the graph is subseted with targets and shortests paths between targets, giving more info to cluster. In the remaining methods this extra information is not included.

I tried including this (in geodesic shortest path terms), and it had no effect, if anything decreased the accuracy score. Wang takes too long, so that was excluded.

mf <- unique(names(unlist(truth$`Geodesic MF`)))

all_dist_MF <- list(
  Wang = GO_similarity(mf,
                       "MF",
                       measure = "Wang"),
  Geodesic = distances(mf_graph),
  Resnik = GO_similarity(mf,
                         "MF",
                         measure = "Resnik"),
  Rel = GO_similarity(mf,
                      "MF",
                      measure = "Rel"),
  Jiang = GO_similarity(mf,
                        "MF",
                        measure = "Jiang"),
  Lin = GO_similarity(mf,
                      "MF",
                      measure = "Lin"),
  anc2vec = anc2vec_dist[mf, mf]
)

bp <- unique(names(unlist(truth$`Geodesic BP`)))

all_dist_BP <- list(
  Wang = GO_similarity(bp,
                       "BP",
                       measure = "Wang"),
  Geodesic = distances(bp_graph),
  Resnik = GO_similarity(bp,
                         "BP",
                         measure = "Resnik"),
  Rel = GO_similarity(bp,
                      "BP",
                      measure = "Rel"),
  Jiang = GO_similarity(bp,
                        "BP",
                        measure = "Jiang"),
  Lin = GO_similarity(bp,
                      "BP",
                      measure = "Lin"),
  anc2vec = anc2vec_dist[bp, bp]

)


all_dist_MF$anc2vec <- 1-as.matrix(all_dist_MF$anc2vec)
all_dist_MF$anc2vec[all_dist_MF$anc2vec<0] <- 0 
all_dist_BP$anc2vec <- 1-as.matrix(all_dist_BP$anc2vec)
all_dist_BP$anc2vec[all_dist_BP$anc2vec<0] <- 0

Regarding negative cosine similarity, -1 is opposite, 0 is unlerated, 1 is same. Cosine distance can be defined as 1 - cosine similarity leading to a range of 0 - 2. This is perhaps not fully meaningful as it violates some assumptions

With that said there is something suspicious here: 1-cosine distance is giving very small negative, ie cosine sim has values above 1. Also, looking at the pd sklearn_cosine_similarity and the np sklearn_cosine_similarity have tiny rounding errors to them

Grid search on Geodesic benchmark

Binary cut does not converge. MCL converges on all methods except the IC methods, and has really poor accuracy (not shown).

Dropping all that are not data.frame.

predictions_topology_MF <- lapply(predictions_topology_MF, \(d){
  d <- lapply(d, \(cl){
    cl[sapply(cl, class) == "data.frame"]
  })
  d[sapply(d, length)>0]
})
predictions_neg_topology_MF <- lapply(predictions_neg_topology_MF, \(d){
  d <- lapply(d, \(cl){
    cl[sapply(cl, class) == "data.frame"]
  })
  d[sapply(d, length)>0]
})
predictions_topology_BP <- lapply(predictions_topology_BP, \(d){

Ordering and colors for subsequent graphs

distance_order <- c("Geodesic", "Wang", "anc2vec", "Resnik", 
                    "Rel", "Jiang", "Lin")

cluster_order <- c("leiden", "fast_greedy", "louvain", "walktrap",
                   "leading_eigen", "mclust", "DTC",
                   "apcluster", "hdbscan", "kmeans")

predictions_topology_MF$L2 <- gsub("dynamicTreeCut","DTC",
                                   predictions_topology_MF$L2)
predictions_topology_MF$L2 <- factor(predictions_topology_MF$L2,
                                     levels = cluster_order)

predictions_topology_BP$L2 <- gsub("dynamicTreeCut","DTC",
                                   predictions_topology_BP$L2)
predictions_topology_BP$L2 <- factor(predictions_topology_BP$L2,
                                     levels = cluster_order)

predictions_neg_topology_MF$L2 <- gsub("dynamicTreeCut","DTC",
                                       predictions_neg_topology_MF$L2)
predictions_neg_topology_MF$L2 <- factor(predictions_neg_topology_MF$L2,
                                         levels = cluster_order)

Schematic of cluster generation

g_all <- subgraph(mf_graph,
              c(neighborhood(mf_graph, 2, "GO:0016209")[[1]],
                neighborhood(mf_graph, 2, "GO:0003674")[[1]]))

#delete some for looks only!
g_all <- delete.vertices(g_all, c("GO:0072541", "GO:0033196"))
#common fig1
V(g_all)$size <- .25
V(g_all)$color <- "#DBA237"

g <- create_layout(g_all, layout = 'nicely')

#before selection
g1 <- ggraph(g) + 
  geom_edge_link(color = "gray", width = .25) + 
  geom_node_point(color = g$color, size = g$size) +
  theme_void()

#select random
s <- "GO:0016684"
g$color[g$name %in% s] <- "red"
g$size[g$name == s] <- 2

g2 <- ggraph(g) + 
  geom_edge_link(color = "gray", size = 10, width = .25) + 
  geom_node_point(color = g$color, size = g$size) +
  theme_void()
## Warning: Ignoring unknown parameters: edge_size
#show sample first
ss <- as_ids(neighborhood(g_all, 2, s)[[1]])
g$size[g$name == ss] <- 1
## Warning in g$name == ss: longer object length is not a multiple of shorter
## object length
g$color[g$name %in% ss] <- "blue"
g$color[g$name %in% s] <- "red"
g3 <- ggraph(g) + 
  geom_edge_link(color = "gray", width = .25) + 
  geom_node_point(color = g$color, size = g$size) +
  theme_void()

#select half

g$color[g$name %in% sample(ss, length(ss)*.5)] <- "gray"
g$color[g$name %in% s] <- "red"

g4 <- ggraph(g) + 
  geom_edge_link(color = "gray", width = .25) + 
  geom_node_point(color = g$color, size = g$size) +
  theme_void()

## Warning: One or more parsing issues, see `problems()` for details
gset <- gset$`GSE31803-GPL570_series_matrix.txt.gz` #the other gpl is a methylation
pdata <- gset@phenoData@data # make proper column names to match toptable
colnames(pdata) <- make.names(colnames(pdata))
pdata$liver <- as.factor(pdata$Stage.ch1)
levels(pdata$liver) <- c("advanced", "mild")

# fix feature data
fdata <- gset@featureData@data[,c("Gene symbol", "Gene ID")]
colnames(fdata) <- c("SYMBOL", "ENTREZID")

# transform the data and remove fundamentaly uninteresting probes.
ex <- exprs(gset)
keep <- !grepl("\\/", fdata$ENTREZID)
ex <- ex[keep,]
fdata <- fdata[keep,]

boxplot(ex)

design <- model.matrix(~0 + liver, pdata)
colnames(design)[1:2] <- c("advanced","mild")

#tempted to use this as the pvalue dist is funky, but no.
fit <- lmFit(ex, design, weights = arrayWeights(ex, design = design))
# fit <- lmFit(ex, design)
cont.matrix <- makeContrasts(advanced - mild, levels = colnames(design))
fit2 <- contrasts.fit(fit, cont.matrix)

# compute statistics and table of top significant genes
fit2 <- eBayes(fit2)
res <- topTable(fit2, adjust="fdr", number=Inf, genelist = fdata)
sum(res$adj.P.Val<0.05)

Enrichment

library(fgsea)
logfc <- res$logFC
names(logfc) <- res$ENTREZID
logfc <- sort(logfc, decreasing = T)

go2eg <- as.list(org.Hs.eg.db::org.Hs.egGO2ALLEGS)
go2eg <- go2eg[names(go2eg) %in% V(mf_graph)$name]
go2eg <- lapply(go2eg, unique)

resEnrich <- fgsea(
  pathways = go2eg,
  stats = logfc, 
  maxSize = 200, #to reduce number of results
  minSize = 10 #to reduce number of results
)
## Warning in preparePathwaysAndStats(pathways, stats, minSize, maxSize, gseaParam, : There are ties in the preranked stats (7.29% of the list).
